.TH "WINDOW.SETTIMEOUT" "3JS" "December 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Window.setTimeout \- Window: setTimeout() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] When the \f[CR]code\f[R] parameter is used, this
method dynamically executes its value as JavaScript.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site\-scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R]
objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]setTimeout()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Window\f[R]
interface sets a timer which executes a function or specified piece of
code once the timer expires.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(code)
setTimeout(code, delay)

setTimeout(func)
setTimeout(func, delay)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1, param2)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1, param2, /* \&..., */ paramN)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]func\f[R]
A \f[CR]function\f[R] to be executed after the timer expires.
.TP
\f[B]code\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R] or a string of arbitrary code that is
compiled and executed every \f[CR]delay\f[R] milliseconds.
This can be used instead of passing a function, but is \f[I]strongly
discouraged\f[R] for the same reasons that make using \f[CR]eval()\f[R]
a security risk.
.TP
\f[B]delay\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
The time that the timer should wait before the specified function or
code is executed, in milliseconds.
Defaults to 0 if not specified.
.RS
.PP
Note:
.IP \(bu 2
The delay has a maximum value of 2147483647 ms \(em specifying larger
values may result in overflow or a 0 value being used.
See maximum delay value below for more information.
.IP \(bu 2
The actual delay may be longer than set.
For example, setting \f[CR]delay\f[R] to 0 will execute in the next
event cycle rather than \(lqimmediately\(rq.
See Reasons for longer delays than specified for more information.
.IP \(bu 2
If the value isn\(cqt a number, implicit type coercion is silently done
on the value to convert it to a number.
This can lead to unexpected and surprising results \(em see Non\-number
delay values are silently coerced into numbers for an example.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]param1\f[R], \&..., \f[B]paramN\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Additional arguments which are passed through to the function specified
by \f[CR]func\f[R].
.SS Return value
A positive integer (typically within the range of 1 to 2,147,483,647)
that uniquely identifies the timer created by the call.
This identifier, often referred to as a \(lqtimeout ID\(rq, can be
passed to \f[CR]clearTimeout()\f[R] to cancel the timer.
.PP
Within the same global environment (e.g., a specific window or worker)
the timeout ID is guaranteed not to be reused for any new timer as long
as the original timer remains active.
However, separate global environments maintain their own independent
pools of timer IDs.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R]
The \f[CR]code\f[R] can\(cqt be parsed as a script.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]code\f[R] parameter is set to a string when Trusted
Types are enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
It is also thrown if the first parameter is not one of the supported
types: a function, string or \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R].
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] function is commonly used to call a function
that is executed just once, after a delay.
You can call \f[CR]Window.clearTimeout()\f[R] to cancel the timeout
before it completes.
.PP
If you wish to call a function repeatedly (e.g., every \f[I]N\f[R]
milliseconds), you can use \f[CR]setInterval()\f[R].
.SS Working with asynchronous functions
\f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] is an asynchronous function, meaning that it
returns immediately after scheduling the callback function or code to
run.
It does not \(lqwait\(rq, blocking execution of the lines of code after
\f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] until the scheduled code has run.
.PP
Consider the following example:
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqthis is the first message\(dq);
}, 5000);
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqthis is the second message\(dq);
}, 3000);
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqthis is the third message\(dq);
}, 1000);

\f[I]// Output:\f[R]

\f[I]// this is the third message\f[R]
\f[I]// this is the second message\f[R]
\f[I]// this is the first message\f[R]
.EE
.PP
The \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] method is called three times, passing a
callback function that logs the order in which \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R]
was called.
Because the earlier methods calls have larger delays, the callback
methods are executed in reverse order to which they were scheduled.
If \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] blocked until the callback completed, the
output would display the messages in order.
.PP
Asynchronous methods are useful because they allow tasks to be run in
parallel when the order of execution does not matter.
If the order that an asynchronous method completes does matter, then you
can use Promises (promise chaining) to wait on the completion of a task.
.SS Functions are called with the global \f[CR]this\f[R]
Methods or functions passed to \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] do not run in the
same execution context as \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R], and hence do not have
the same \f[CR]this\f[R] as the function that called
\f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R].
Instead the called function has a \f[CR]this\f[R] keyword set to the
\f[CR]window\f[R] (or \f[CR]global\f[R]) object.
This problem is explained in detail in the JavaScript reference.
.PP
The following example demonstrates how this can cause unexpected
behavior:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myObject = {
  log() {
    console.log(\(gamyProperty: ${\f[B]this\f[R].myProperty}\(ga);
  },
  myProperty: 12,
};

myObject.log(); \f[I]// myProperty: 12\f[R]
setTimeout(myObject.log, 1000); \f[I]// myProperty: undefined\f[R]
.EE
.PP
You can use a wrapper function, such as an arrow function, to adopt the
\f[CR]this\f[R] of the function in which \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] is
called (arrow functions have a lexical \f[CR]this\f[R]).
.PP
You can test this with the following code:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Arrow function callback\f[R]
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] myObject.log(), 2000); \f[I]// myProperty: 12 after 2 seconds\f[R]

\f[I]// Anonymous function callback\f[R]
setTimeout(\f[B]function\f[R] () {
  myObject.log();
}, 3000); \f[I]// myProperty: 12 after 3 seconds\f[R]
.EE
.PP
You might also use the \f[CR]Function.prototype.bind()\f[R] method,
which lets you specify the value that should be used as \f[CR]this\f[R]
for all calls to a given function.
That lets you bypass problems where it\(cqs unclear what \f[CR]this\f[R]
will be, depending on the context from which your function was called:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myArray = [\(dqzero\(dq, \(dqone\(dq, \(dqtwo\(dq];
\f[B]const\f[R] myBoundMethod = \f[B]function\f[R] (sProperty) {
  console.log(\f[B]arguments\f[R].length > 0 ? \f[B]this\f[R][sProperty] : \f[B]this\f[R]);
}.bind(myArray);

myBoundMethod(); \f[I]// prints \(dqzero,one,two\(dq because \(aqthis\(aq is bound to myArray in the function\f[R]
myBoundMethod(1); \f[I]// prints \(dqone\(dq\f[R]
setTimeout(myBoundMethod, 1.0 * 1000); \f[I]// still prints \(dqzero,one,two\(dq after 1 second because of the binding\f[R]
setTimeout(myBoundMethod, 1.5 * 1000, \(dq1\(dq); \f[I]// prints \(dqone\(dq after 1.5 seconds\f[R]
.EE
.SS Non\-number delay values are silently coerced into numbers
If \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] is called with \f[I]delay\f[R] value
that\(cqs not a number, implicit type coercion is silently done on the
value to convert it to a number.
For example, the following code incorrectly uses the string
\f[CR]\(dq1000\(dq\f[R] for the \f[I]delay\f[R] value, rather than the
number \f[CR]1000\f[R] \(en but it nevertheless works, because when the
code runs, the string is coerced into the number \f[CR]1000\f[R], and so
the code executes 1 second later.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqDelayed for 1 second.\(dq);
}, \(dq1000\(dq);
.EE
.PP
In many cases, the implicit type coercion can lead to unexpected and
surprising results.
For example, when the following code runs, the string
\f[CR]\(dq1 second\(dq\f[R] ultimately gets coerced into the number
\f[CR]0\f[R] \(em and so, the code executes with zero delay.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqDelayed for 1 second.\(dq);
}, \(dq1 second\(dq);
.EE
.PP
Therefore, don\(cqt use strings for the \f[I]delay\f[R] value but
instead always use numbers:
.PP
\f[B]Good\f[R]
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\(dqDelayed for 1 second.\(dq);
}, 1000);
.EE
.SS Maximum delay value
The \f[CR]delay\f[R] argument is converted to a signed 32\-bit integer,
which limits the value to 2147483647 ms, or roughly 24.8 days.
Delays of more than this value will cause an integer overflow.
So for example, this code:
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dqhi!\(dq), 2 ** 32 \- 5000);
.EE
.PP
\&...results in the timeout being executed immediately (since
\f[CR]2**32 \- 5000\f[R] overflows to a negative number), while the
following code:
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dqhi!\(dq), 2 ** 32 + 5000);
.EE
.PP
\&...results in the timeout being executed after approximately 5
seconds.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] In Node.js, any timeout larger than 2,147,483,647 ms
results in immediate execution.
.RE
.SS Reasons for longer delays than specified
There are a number of reasons why a timeout may take longer to fire than
anticipated.
This section describes the most common reasons.
.SS Nested timeouts
As specified in the \c
.UR https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/timers-and-user-prompts.html#timers
HTML standard
.UE \c
, browsers will enforce a minimum timeout of 4 milliseconds once a
nested call to \f[CR]setTimeout\f[R] has been scheduled 5 times.
.PP
This can be seen in the following example, in which we nest a call to
\f[CR]setTimeout\f[R] with a delay of \f[CR]0\f[R] milliseconds, and log
the delay each time the handler is called.
The first four times, the delay is approximately 0 milliseconds, and
after that it is approximately 4 milliseconds:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqrun\(dq>Run</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]table\f[R]>
  <\f[B]thead\f[R]>
    <\f[B]tr\f[R]>
      <\f[B]th\f[R]>Previous</\f[B]th\f[R]>
      <\f[B]th\f[R]>This</\f[B]th\f[R]>
      <\f[B]th\f[R]>Actual delay</\f[B]th\f[R]>
    </\f[B]tr\f[R]>
  </\f[B]thead\f[R]>
  <\f[B]tbody\f[R] id=\(dqlog\(dq></\f[B]tbody\f[R]>
</\f[B]table\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] last = 0;
\f[B]let\f[R] iterations = 10;

\f[B]function\f[R] timeout() {
  \f[I]// log the time of this call\f[R]
  log(\f[B]new\f[R] Date().getMilliseconds());
  \f[I]// if we are not finished, schedule the next call\f[R]
  \f[B]if\f[R] (iterations\-\- > 0) {
    setTimeout(timeout, 0);
  }
}

\f[B]function\f[R] run() {
  \f[I]// clear the log\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] log = document.querySelector(\(dq#log\(dq);
  \f[B]while\f[R] (log.lastElementChild) {
    log.removeChild(log.lastElementChild);
  }

  \f[I]// initialize iteration count and the starting timestamp\f[R]
  iterations = 10;
  last = \f[B]new\f[R] Date().getMilliseconds();
  \f[I]// start timer\f[R]
  setTimeout(timeout, 0);
}

\f[B]function\f[R] log(now) {
  \f[I]// log the last timestamp, the new timestamp, and the difference\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] tableBody = document.getElementById(\(dqlog\(dq);
  \f[B]const\f[R] logRow = tableBody.insertRow();
  logRow.insertCell().textContent = last;
  logRow.insertCell().textContent = now;
  logRow.insertCell().textContent = now \- last;
  last = now;
}

document.querySelector(\(dq#run\(dq).addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, run);
.EE
.SS Timeouts in inactive tabs
To reduce the load (and associated battery usage) from background tabs,
browsers will enforce a minimum timeout delay in inactive tabs.
It may also be waived if a page is playing sound using a Web Audio API
\f[CR]AudioContext\f[R].
.PP
The specifics of this are browser\-dependent:
.IP \(bu 2
Firefox Desktop has a minimum timeout of 1 second for inactive tabs.
.IP \(bu 2
Firefox for Android has a minimum timeout of 15 minutes for inactive
tabs and may unload them entirely.
.IP \(bu 2
Firefox does not throttle inactive tabs if the tab contains an
\f[CR]AudioContext\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Chrome uses different levels of throttling depending on the tab
activity:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Minimal throttling\f[R]: Applies to timers when the page is
visible, has made sound recently, or is otherwise considered active by
Chrome.
Timers run close to the requested interval.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Throttling\f[R]: Applies to timers when minimal throttle conditions
are not met and any of these conditions are true:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Nesting count (i.e., number of chained timer calls) is lower than 5.
.IP \(bu 2
Page has been invisible for less than 5 minutes.
.IP \(bu 2
WebRTC is active.
.RE
Timers in this state are checked once per second, which may be batched
together with other timers that have similar timeouts.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Intensive throttling\f[R]: Introduced in Chrome 88 (January 2021).
Applies to timers when neither minimal throttling nor throttling
conditions are met, and all of the following conditions are met:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Nesting count is 5 or higher.
.IP \(bu 2
Page has been invisible for more than 5 minutes.
.IP \(bu 2
Page has been silent for more than 30 seconds.
.IP \(bu 2
WebRTC is inactive.
.RE
Timers in this state are checked once per minute, which may be batched
together with other timers that have similar timeouts.
.RE
.SS Throttling of tracking scripts
Firefox enforces additional throttling for scripts that it recognizes as
tracking scripts.
When running in the foreground, the throttling minimum delay is still
4ms.
In background tabs, however, the throttling minimum delay is 10,000 ms,
or 10 seconds, which comes into effect 30 seconds after a document has
first loaded.
.PP
See \c
.UR https://wiki.mozilla.org/Security/Tracking_protection
Tracking Protection
.UE \c
\ for more details.
.SS Late timeouts
The timeout can also fire later than expected if the page (or the
OS/browser) is busy with other tasks.
One important case to note is that the function or code snippet cannot
be executed until the thread that called \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] has
terminated.
For example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] foo() {
  console.log(\(dqfoo has been called\(dq);
}
setTimeout(foo, 0);
console.log(\(dqAfter setTimeout\(dq);
.EE
.PP
Will write to the console:
.IP
.EX
After setTimeout
foo has been called
.EE
.PP
This is because even though \f[CR]setTimeout\f[R] was called with a
delay of zero, it\(cqs placed on a queue and scheduled to run at the
next opportunity; not immediately.
Currently\-executing code must complete before functions on the queue
are executed, thus the resulting execution order may not be as expected.
.SS Deferral of timeouts during pageload
Firefox will defer firing \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] timers while the
current tab is loading.
Firing is deferred until the main thread is deemed idle (similar to
\f[CR]Window.requestIdleCallback()\f[R]), or until the load event is
fired.
.SS WebExtension background pages and timers
In WebExtensions, \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] does not work reliably.
Extension authors should use the \f[CR]alarms\f[R] API instead.
.SS Security considerations
The method can be used to execute arbitrary input passed in the
\f[CR]code\f[R] parameter.
If the input is a potentially unsafe string provided by a user, this is
a possible vector for Cross\-site\-scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
For example, the following code shows how \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] might
execute \f[CR]untrustedCode\f[R] provided by a user:
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedCode = \(dqalert(\(aqPotentially evil code!\(aq);\(dq;
\f[B]const\f[R] id = setTimeout(untrustedCode, 1000);
.EE
.PP
Websites with a Content Security Policy (CSP) that specifies
\f[CR]script\-src\f[R] or \f[CR]default\-src\f[R] will prevent such code
running by default.
You can specify \f[CR]unsafe\-eval\f[R] in your CSP to allow
\f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] to execute, but this is unsafe as it disables
one of the main protections of CSP.
See Inline JavaScript in the CSP guide.
.PP
If you must allow the scripts to run via \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] you can
mitigate these issues by always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R]
objects instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function.
.PP
To allow \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] to run, you will additionally need to
specify the \f[CR]trusted\-types\-eval\f[R] keyword in your CSP
\f[CR]script\-src\f[R] directive.
This acts in the same way as \f[CR]unsafe\-eval\f[R], but \f[I]only\f[R]
allows the method to evaluate if trusted types are enabled (if you were
to use \f[CR]unsafe\-eval\f[R] it would allow execution even on browsers
that do not support trusted types).
.PP
For example, the required CSP for your site might look like this:
.IP
.EX
Content\-Security\-Policy: require\-trusted\-types\-for \(aqscript\(aq; script\-src \(aq<your_allowlist>\(aq \(aqtrusted\-types\-eval\(aq
.EE
.PP
The behavior of the transformation function will depend on the specific
use case that requires a user provided script.
If possible you should lock the allowed scripts to exactly the code that
you trust to run.
If that is not possible, you might allow or block the use of certain
functions within the provided string.
.SH EXAMPLES
Note that these examples omit the use of trusted types for brevity.
See Using \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R] in \f[CR]eval()\f[R] for code showing
the expected approach.
.SS Setting and clearing timeouts
The following example sets up two simple buttons in a web page and hooks
them to the \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] and \f[CR]clearTimeout()\f[R]
routines.
Pressing the first button will set a timeout which shows a message after
two seconds and stores the timeout id for use by
\f[CR]clearTimeout()\f[R].
You may optionally cancel this timeout by pressing on the second button.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqshow\(dq>Show a message after two seconds</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqcancel\(dq>Cancel message before it happens</\f[B]button\f[R]>

<\f[B]div\f[R] id=\(dqoutput\(dq></\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] timeoutID;

\f[B]function\f[R] setOutput(outputContent) {
  document.querySelector(\(dq#output\(dq).textContent = outputContent;
}

\f[B]function\f[R] delayedMessage() {
  setOutput(\(dq\(dq);
  timeoutID = setTimeout(setOutput, 2 * 1000, \(dqThat was really slow!\(dq);
}

\f[B]function\f[R] clearMessage() {
  clearTimeout(timeoutID);
}

document.getElementById(\(dqshow\(dq).addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, delayedMessage);
document.getElementById(\(dqcancel\(dq).addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, clearMessage);
.EE
.SS Result
See also the \f[CR]clearTimeout()\f[R] example.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
